Yes, there are several metadata fields that are required for DICOM images to be viewable in most viewers. These include:
1. SOP Class UID: This is a unique identifier that specifies the type of image and the type of information it contains. It is used to identify the type of viewer that can display the image.
2. Study Instance UID: This is a unique identifier that is assigned to a specific study that contains the image. It is used to group together all of the images that are part of the same study.
3. Series Instance UID: This is a unique identifier that is assigned to a specific series of images. It is used to group together all of the images that belong to the same series.
4. Image Position (Patient): This field defines the position of the image in relation to the patient's body. It is used to ensure that the image is displayed in the correct orientation.
5. Image Orientation (Patient): This field defines the orientation of the image in relation to the patient's body. It is used to ensure that the image is displayed in the correct orientation.
6. Pixel Spacing: This field defines the physical distance between each pixel in the image. It is used to ensure that the image is displayed at the correct size.
7. Bits Allocated: This field defines the number of bits that are allocated for each pixel in the image. It is used to ensure that the image is displayed with the correct level of detail.
8. Bits Stored: This field defines the actual number of bits that are used to store each pixel value. It is used to ensure that the image is displayed with the correct level of detail.
These are some of the key metadata fields that are required for DICOM images to be viewable in most viewers. Other metadata fields may also be required depending on the specific viewer being used.
